[I'm transitioning to the Worldometer website as it has been more up to date in the evening than the CSSE site these past 2 days. Hence, some of the numbers in the table may seem a bit off from the previous day.

According to the data on the Worldometer website, the total number of cases of COVID-19 worldwide is now 134 804, with 80 814 cases reported by China (closer to the figures presented in the China update in section [2] below). There are now a total of 53 990 confirmed cases of COVID-19 reported from 127 countries/locations outside mainland China representing an increase of 8844 cases when compared with the CSSE data on 11 Mar 2020 with Italy accounting for 2651 of the newly reported cases, Iran for 1075 of newly reported cases, and South Korea for 224 of the newly reported cases. There were 14 other countries with more than 50 newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, with 4 countries reporting more cases in 24 hours than South Korea: Spain, 869; Germany, 779; France, 592; USA, 451; Switzerland, 216; Sweden, 187; Norway, 171; Denmark, 158; UK, 131; Austria, 115; Netherlands, 111; Belgium, 85; Japan, 52; and Finland, 50. Of the 14 countries, 12 are in Europe, 1 is in North America, and 1 is in the Western Pacific. A global total of 4984 deaths have been reported, 1807 outside mainland China.

For the 15th consecutive day, more cases have been reported from outside mainland China than within mainland China. - Mod.MPP]

