Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Note that the reporting interval is now midnight to midnight, presenting the full calendar day. In the past 24 hours, the tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in South Korea has increased by 110 cases and 1 death as compared with yesterday's 24 hour period (11-12 Mar 2020) when there were 114 newly confirmed cases. The epicenter of this outbreak is still Daegu province with 5928 reported cases and the surrounding province of Gyeongbuk with 1147 reported cases. Although daily case counts are slowing down with only 4 newly confirmed cases in Gyeongbuk in the past 24 hours, and only 61 cases reported from Daegu. Provinces reporting near or more than 100 cases include Gyeonggi (185). Seoul (225), Chungnam (115), and Busan (100). In the past 24 hours (12-13 Mar 2020), 9 provinces reported no new cases (up from 8 yesterday 11 Mar 2020),

The English language update page for yesterday (11 Mar 2020; (https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=&bid=0030) included the following information:
- A current total of 99 confirmed cases have been reported from a call center in Guro-gu since [8 Mar 2020]. Epidemiological investigation and contact tracing are underway. Out of 208 workers at the call center on the 11th floor, 80 cases are confirmed. Self-quarantine measures have been taken by 553 workers who work on the 7th through 9th floors of the same building.

- In light of the recent rise in case clusters from closed spaces including gym facilities and call centers, "Guidelines for intense management of business entities* for COVID-19 prevention" have been created by Korea's public health authorities. (*includes call centers, Internet cafes, gyms, religious gatherings, private academies, etc.)

- To prevent further imported cases, special immigration procedures will be expanded to the European region in response to the recent rapid increase of local transmission. The procedures will begin to take effect at 0:00 of [15 Mar 2020] for all Korean and international travelers arriving after having visited or lived in France, Germany, Spain, the UK, or the Netherlands.

- KCDC urged everyone to keep strict adherence to personal hygiene and social distancing measures, including covering sneezes and coughs with arm sleeves to prevent transmission via respiratory droplets and refraining from visiting closed community spaces or public gatherings.

- KCDC also encouraged businesses and workplaces to adopt remote working environments for employees such as work-at-home and online collaboration.

- Extra care should be taken to keep clean any frequently used surfaces in living spaces. Individuals with fever and respiratory symptoms should refrain from leaving home including going to work or school and watch the symptoms for the next 3-4 days.

A map of South Korea showing provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7084577,195. - Mod.MPP]

