--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@rpromedmail.org>

[The tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Italy is now 15 113, including 1016 deaths, up from 12 462 cases and 827 deaths reported on 11 Mar 2020. The 24-hour change between 11 and 12 Mar 2020 was 2651 newly confirmed cases, compared with 2313 newly confirmed cases between 10 and 11 Mar 2020. Cases continue to be concentrated in Lombardy (8725), the epicenter of the outbreak, Emilia-Romagna (1947), and Venice (1384), all in the northern part of the country. These 3 provinces account for 76.0% of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours.

On 9 Mar 2020, Italy announced a lockdown for the northern provinces where the outbreak was concentrated. On 10 Mar 2020, this was changed to be countrywide. Today (11 Mar 2020), Italy announced the closure of non-essential businesses. As for seeing an impact, one shouldn't expect to see an impact until at least one incubation period has passed, as there are newly infected individuals who are still in their incubation period for up to 14 days. As mentioned before, the Public Health world is looking at Italy to see if this is feasible and if it has an impact in terms of slowing down transmission of the virus.

A dashboard similar to the Hopkins dashboard, including a map, produced by Italy showing the situation in near real time, can be found at http://opendatadpc.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/b0c68bce2cce478eaac82fe38d4138b1.

A map of Italy showing regions can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/italy/regions.html and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7084577,75. - Mod.MPP]

